HOUSE JOINT RESOLUTION 1164
By Gant
A RESOLUTION to honor the memory of Henry Wetter Morgan of
Memphis.
WHEREAS, the members of this General Assembly were greatly saddened to learn of
the passing of Henry Wetter Morgan of Memphis; and
WHEREAS, Henry Morgan was an exemplary public servant and consummate
professional who worked assiduously to improve the quality of life for his fellow citizens in
numerous capacities; and
WHEREAS, born in Memphis on October 25, 1943, Mr. Morgan was the son of Elise
Wetter Morgan and Allen Benners Morgan; he was raised in Memphis and attended Pentecost
Garrison, Presbyterian Day School, and Episcopal High School and graduated from Memphis
University School; and
WHEREAS, Henry Morgan achieved the rank of Eagle Scout at the early age of thirteen
and excelled in tennis and racquetball, winning many trophies; nothing pleased him more than
consistently beating his older brother in tennis; and
WHEREAS, following high school, he attended the University of North Carolina, where
he served as president of the Delta Kappa Epsilon Fraternity, majored in economics, and
graduated in 1965; the friendships he formed during these years continued throughout his life;
and
WHEREAS, after college, Henry Morgan joined the Air National Guard, serving as a
medic and, simultaneously, began his career at Boyle Investment Company in the insurance
department before shifting to the mortgage banking department; and
WHEREAS, in the mid-1970s, Mr. Morgan took over and ran the real estate company's
investment property division, leading the development of office, retail, and multifamily
HJR1164
016057
- 1 -

properties; in this role, he was directly involved with or oversaw the development of more than
twenty million square feet of commercial space in the Memphis and Nashville markets; and
WHEREAS, a remarkable leader with visionary insight, Henry Morgan guided the
company's growth while serving as president from 1985 to 2012 and later as co-chair emeritus
alongside his brother-in-law, John Bayard Boyle, Jr.; and
WHEREAS, he often said what he valued most were the people he worked with, and he
gave credit to them for the company's success; and
WHEREAS, in 2001, Mr. Morgan was inducted into the Society of Entrepreneurs, and in
2012, he was inducted into the Memphis Area Association of Realtors Commercial Hall of
Fame; and
WHEREAS, deeply devoted to his community, Henry Morgan served on numerous
boards including the board of directors for the Memphis Area Chamber of Commerce and the
board of the Baptist Memorial Healthcare Foundation as a member and past chairman; and
WHEREAS, Mr. Morgan was a board member of the Memphis Arts Council, Memphis
University School, Grace St. Luke's Episcopal School, Trezevant Manor, and Boys & Girls Clubs
of Memphis; he also served as a vestry member of St. John's Episcopal Church; and
WHEREAS, Henry Morgan was an accomplished sportsman and was passionate about
conservation, supporting organizations including Ducks Unlimited, Delta Wildlife, the Wild
Turkey Federation, the Wolf River Conservancy, The Nature Conservancy, and the TennGreen
Land Conservancy; he found his greatest joy being with family and friends in the outdoors,
whether in a field, the woods, or fly fishing on a river; and
WHEREAS, Mr. Morgan lived by unwavering values: give your best, do what is right, and
treat others with dignity and respect; he had a friendly and welcoming manner, with a smile that
could light up the room; and
- 2 - 016057

WHEREAS, others consistently sought his counsel because of his sound judgement and
the value he placed on fairness; and
WHEREAS, Henry Morgan will be remembered as a devoted husband, father,
grandfather, friend, and a respected business leader, always conducting himself with the
highest standards of honor; and
WHEREAS, he is survived by his beloved wife, Snowden Boyle Morgan; sons, Henry
Wetter (Mena) Morgan, Jr., and Bayard Boyle Morgan (Jane Hart); cherished grandchildren,
Elliott Snowden Morgan, Sarah McLean Morgan, Bayard Wyatt Morgan, Gwin Anne Marguerite
Morgan, and Henry Kemp Morgan; siblings, Allen Benners (Musette) Morgan, Jr., and Elise
Morgan Stratton; and a host of nieces, nephews, and cousins; and
WHEREAS, Mr. Morgan leaves behind an indelible legacy of integrity and probity in
public life, compassion and loyalty in private life, and diligence and dedication in all his chosen
endeavors; and
WHEREAS, it is fitting that the members of this General Assembly should remember the
bountiful life of this exceptional public servant and human being; now, therefore,
BE IT RESOLVED BY THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES OF THE ONE HUNDRED
FOURTEENTH GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, THE SENATE
CONCURRING, that we honor the memory of Henry Wetter Morgan, reflecting fondly upon his
impeccable character and his stalwart commitment to living the examined life with courage and
conviction.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that we extend our sympathy and offer our condolences
to the family of Mr. Morgan.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that an appropriate copy of this resolution be prepared
for presentation with this final clause omitted from such copy and upon proper request made to
- 3 - 016057

the appropriate clerk, the language appearing immediately following the State seal appear
without House or Senate designation.
